nfor the week ending June 16 show:\nJune 16. Inc. Dec.\nNew York.......... $1,797 406.000\n5.742.000\n152.023.00 17.6\nJune 9,\n21.9 \u00a72,261,163,000\n74\n3.207, 60\nJs, registered, 1900 wtene 100%\n2a. compon. 190............. TU EA\n0\n3s, registered 1908.18.......... TIRE WN\n3s, Banas is susneinnsen secesss 101\n4s, registered, 193............. SEARLE 111%\nis, He ARE Th 114g\nPanama Canal 10-30 yr. 2s reg, 19%6......\nPanama Canal 10-3 yr. 25 reg, 1938.....\nPhilippine Islands land pur. &s. 1914-34. Joos\nNew York, June I7.-\u2014~Misoellaneous bond quota\ntions:\nBu TER Fal fh. ii diirnas 98%\nA TBE FO Bh. ivaicnainy tag 0%\nAtlantic Coast Line 45..........cconuuee sraniannes SO\nBaltimore one 8. W. giv, 3fs..... ERNEST, Rg\nChesapeake Ohio gnl. 43s... ...covvnnnninsnian 0m\nChesapeake Ohio evi. 4%s..... shsres PPE B95\nChicago, Buriigton Quincy 4s\nC,R 1 &P rig \u00a5T\nColorado Southern $1.......\nDelaware Hudson cvt. 4s.... 7%\nIntbo,-Met, 4s srsnsatensaney THR.\nN.Y. Gas E. LH. Power 58.0............. wm\nXN. XX. NX. HH. 5&8 cvit. debep. 6a.............. 132\nN'Y J, Wier icsmrrssnsisernrsaees 9%\nPeonsylvatiia JM8 .....cceuvvarrirer ses suirirar neces Fh%\nReading gul. 45......cc.coviininnnn ER rrrinns\nCE ARERR Ree, 81\nSeaboard Air Line adi 58........cconcvarinnninans 73\nSouthern Pacific 20l, 43... .ccoccviinnnninirnannss 99%\nSouthern Pacific rig. 4s.......... es srnay sesnneine HH.\nUlster Delaware 58....... reatantiz esis canisters 103\nUnderground Electric of London Ss. snessn Bf\nput States Bteel 8. F. 58......ci0n eres ie S108\nWabash HE Becciiviuaicnnin PN i\nWestern Union 48.ccverrereer reersrrsveerrey JER\nrn\nTotal sales, $035.000,\nNEW YORK PRODUCE.\nNew York, June 17.-BUTTER\u2014Receipts to-day\n9321 packages. The market rules steady, Creamer\nspecials, 28; creamery extras, 2%; creamery firsts\n6%: State dairy, good to choice, 27; process spe\ncials, BL: Western imitation creamery firsts, 25.\nCHEESE-Reeeipts\u00ab to-day, 2415 boxes. Skimi\nare dull. State, whole milk, new specials, 15\nState, whole milk, fancy, colored, 14; State, whole\nmilk, fancy, white, 13%; skims, specials, 11%.\nEGGS\u2014Receipts to-day, 19,327 cases, The market\nis essentially unchanged in. tone and prices, State,\nPennsylvania, and near-by hennery, white, fancy,\n2; State Pennsylvania brown hennery, fancy, 23%:\nfresh-gathered extras, 22; fresh-gathered extra\nfirsts, 20%.\nMILLFEED\u2014 Weaker; trade moderate. Spring\nbran, 19.35; standard middlings, 20.40; city bran,\n18.75, in bulk; Western red dog. Z.90. to arrive;\nwinter wheat bran, in 100-pound sacks, tc arrive,\n22.60.\nOATS~Steady: light demand. No. 2 white, 43a\n3%; No. 3 white, 42a42%; No. 4 white, 4ladls;\nnatural and clipped white, on track, 41a4l.\nFLOUR\u2014Inactive and unsettled. Kansas straights,\n4.70a5.00 in sacks: soft straights, 4.30a4.65, in bar\nrela; spring patents, 5255.60, in barrels; spring\nclears, 4.252140, New Kansas straights, to arrive,\n4.800475.\n\n\nRYE FLOUR-Steady; small inguiry. Choice\nbrands quoted at 4.10a4.50,\nCORNMEAL~\u2014Steady business 4s moderate. Kiln\ndried for export, 3.30; coarse meal, in bags, 1.30a\n1a,\ni\n\nBEEF--Steady; fair demand. Packet, 17.00a18.00;\nfamily, 19.50a20.00.\nPORK-Stronger, but inactive, Mess, 24.25a25.00;\nfamily, 2600.26.50,\nHAY Receipts, 1,201 tons; firm: fair demand.\nPrime timothy, L115; No. 1, 1.12%: No. 2, 1001.05:\nNo. 3, 55a.\nJOU Se Bn ET ian E. Thom ins, green, cach, 1.Malis.\nSTRAW-\u2014Receipts, 50 tons; steady; light trade.\nLong rye quoted at 50a55,\nQuotations furnished by W. B. Hibbs Co,\n\u2018members of the New York Stock Exchange, Hibbs\nBuilding:\nx. QIViaenG. EE\nNew York, June 17.\u2014~The market broke in the last\nhour on what appeared to be a further drive by\nthe bear element, with support in the oid\noptions withdrawn temporarily at least. This caused\nscattered Jiguidation, and the decline\nconsiderable stop-loss orders from trailers.\nPrices broke thirty points for July and Angnst\nOpen, High,\n500 BY\neta et ew\nea v Risa RRA Sa AR 1239 1245\nirssanverrnsianians 10a 1038\n$i)\nBE\nhe\nLE)\nRAILROADS.\nGOVERNMENT BONDS,\nMISCELLANEOUS BONDS.\nCOTTON MARKET\nWEEKLY REVIEW OF TRADE\nBusiness Outlook in General Is Better Than Last Week\nor That of a Year Apo.\nSh Ares DS \"SY Columbia Heights\u2014Lot 3, block 31; Ulysses 8. Cat.\nNew York, June 17.\u2014Bradstreet's review\nof the stata of trade to-morrow will gay:\n\u201cirregularity and relative quiet are\nstill the ruling features in trade and in\ndustry, but evidences of improvement in\nWestern distribution are rather sharply\nin contract with the reports of slow trade\nrecently received. Warmer weather is\nthe key to the better crop and trade re\nports received this week from the West,\nNorthwest, and Southwest, while cool,\nmoist conditions along the Atlantic coast,\nnow disappearing, have been a bar to\ntrade and crop development in the East.\noo oon Gerace vs. Lambert: sale setarnable ington Loan and Trust Company, trustee, t%0\nNo 5. Nourse va, Williame; sale ratified nisi; EA X.\noo 16 Jose: oh Sift\nil trustees fixed at $5,000. Attomey, H., 8.\n\u20180. 237 \u00a33 et nx homas Dent, $10.\nN 373. Hill vs, Mathiot; auditors ratified. At- Washington circ} a ape Eridt Ghd New\ntormeys, Maddox Gathy and H. Syme\u2014Ralston, aT shes J and\nRidden Richardson. 4; Jom W.\nMount Pleasant\u2014Squar 2595, Jots 92, 62, and 94:\nMatthews, Le Droit t\u2014Lat 19, block 8; Alfred A. Graeve\n\u201cRelatively best reports\u2019 come from\nWestern cities and towns, while country\ntrade, though better, is lower to respond,\nowing to farmers being busy in work on\nhitherto delayed crops. The improvement\nIn agricultural matters ig, however, not\nuniform, even in the West, Winter wheat,\noats, and corn have responded to better\ngrowing weather, while lack of rain is\nchecking otherwise satisfactory growth\nof spring wheat. Latest advices are of\nrains in the Canadian Northwest, and\ngive hope of needed moisture arriving in\nthe Northwestern States, where temper\natures are very high.\u201d\n\nLOCAL FINANCIAL GOSSIP.\nTrading on the Washington Stock Ex\nchange yesterday was better distributed\nthan for several days, and for the most\npart at slightly advanced prices. Wash\nington Rallway Common sold at to 3%\na pot above previous sales. The pre\nferred was bid in as much as offered at\n5% to 4%.\nGas also wag in some demand, with\nlimited offerings, selling at 71%. George\ntown Gas, which rarely enters into the\ntrading, came out with twenty shares at\n86, which for a long time has been the\ncurrent price.\nThe type machines attracted most at\ntention, Mergenthaler selling at 218 in\nsmall lots and Lanston coming out quite\nfreely, after call at 78% to 79. Lanston\nrights sold at 3%.\nA letter was read from the Merchants\nand Mechanics Savings Bank announcing\nthat the usual semi-annual dividend of 3\nper cent will be paid on July 1\nSeven hundred and thirty thousand dol\nlars is a big sum for one concern to pay\nin the form of indebtedness and fixed\ncharges, yet that is what the Maryland\nTrust Company announces will be paid\nby the Houston Oil Company to its cred\nitors on July 1. The trust company is\ntrustee for the Texas concern. It will\nreceive on the first of next month $835 600\non account of stumpage contracts and\n$105,000 interest on $3,500,000 of second\nseries of 6 per cent certificates.\nOn August 1 the Maryland company\nwill disburse in payment of series N, first\nissue of Houston Oil certificates, $490,000,\nand on the same date will pay $7,150 in\nterest on the outstanding certificates, and\n$105,900 interest on the second issue of\ncertificates.\nWith the payment of $4%.000 principal.\nthere will still be outstanding of the\nfirst certificates $2,865,000 of an original\nissue of $7,200,000 and the full issue of\n$3,000,000 of second certificates,\nThe Houston Oil Company Is liquidating\nits indebtedness at the rate of about\n$1,000,600 a year. The last of the cer\ntificates will be paid off on August 1, 1918.\nSalhi\nSeptumber......... HATE\nWASHINGTON STOCK MARKET.\nSales\u2014Regular call, 12 o'clock noon:\nPotomac Eleciric cons. 5s, $1,000 at 101,\nWashington Railway Electric com, 35 at 343%,\n2 at 3%.\nWashington Railway Electric pid, 5 at 88%, 8\nai 88%, 3 at 38%.\nWashington Gas, 1 at TI%.\nGeorgetown Gas, 10 at 10 at 8.\nMergenthaler, 2 at 218.\nLanston rights, 100 at 3%.\nSccond National Dank, 16 at 180, 5 at 180,\nUnited States Trust, 10 at 115%.\nAfter call;\nLanston, 20 at 78%, at T8%, 20 at 78%, 40 at\nBY, 100 at 70,\nLanston rights, 100 at 35\nFollowing are the bid and asked prices on yester\nday's Washington Stock Exchange:\nGAS BONDS\n\n\nDid. Asked.\nGeorgetown Gas \u00a78...0vvviirrsnrsrinnrnns 108% 112\nWashington Gas 4.......c000vvnees wvaen 18 110\nWashington Gas cert. 8s.................. 105 119\nRAILROAD BONDS.\nCapital Teastibh........coocianacniviees ine 115 ny\nAnzeostia and Potomac 58..........c0000. 199 101%\nCb and Suburban 88....ccivviirrenarnnee 02 103%\nColumbia Ja... cr sine enss cornna ee 1014 CIR\nColhwentia 6s 105 08\nSolon F8..... coi ceuiveissnssinessoran 18 hii]\nWashington Railway Electric 8s. 1\nWashington, Alex, Mt. Vernon 3s... o\nColofilal- Beaoh 38... ...cccon cs vannsis sana 7% 1%\nMISCELLANEOUS BONDS.\nPotomac Electric cons. 83................ 0% i\nPotomac\u201d Electric Light 58.....cc00ven. vs LL 108%\nChesapeake Potomae Telephone 8s... 104 jie\nAmerican Tel, and Tel. 45.....cc000ennen 10 ET\nEmerson Steam Pump 68.......c00ven..nn. 9% 190\nPUBLIC UTILITY STOCKS.\nCapital Peatdiim, ir a ae eae hv 130\nWashington Railway El etre com... 34% E51\nWashington Railway Electric pfd.... 8%\nWashington, Alex. and Mt. Vernon..... 9 rash\nNorfolk and Washington Steamboat.... 22 &5\nWashington GAs. 0a iii bs bs\nGeorgetown Gas... occa aan 0 0\nAmerican Telephone Telegraph....... Th] \u201creve\nTYPE MACHINE STOCKS,\nMergenthaler dx sinadinan nny ans ei